00:14:53.263 --> 00:14:58.720
you're doing this on a computer
but you have some type of
internet telephone connection

00:14:58.720 --> 00:15:02.716
whether it's Skype or Google
voice or whatever else and
you're using a shared whiteboard,

00:15:02.716 --> 00:15:06.956
kind of something like what I'm writing on
right now, but it's live and in real time.

00:15:06.956 --> 00:15:08.953
You could actually even record.

00:15:08.953 --> 00:15:11.869
(writing) You could
record the interaction.

00:15:11.869 --> 00:15:14.052
One, that's valuable from
a safety point of view,

00:15:14.052 --> 00:15:18.457
but it's also valuable to have this
huge library of other interactions that

00:15:18.457 --> 00:15:20.750
maybe if I can't find a tutor immediately,

00:15:20.750 --> 00:15:24.259
I can dig through the recordings of
other people who've had the same problem

00:15:24.259 --> 00:15:26.259
and I can get my question answered.

00:15:26.259 --> 00:15:32.331
The power here is not only are you able
to leverage all of the student body

00:15:32.331 --> 00:15:35.054
of this virtual academy
to teach each other,

00:15:35.054 --> 00:15:40.744
but you also are doing it in
a very data rich environment
because you know what happens.

00:15:40.744 --> 00:15:45.889
Each of these, in isolation, I
think, is already a huge value add,

00:15:45.889 --> 00:15:49.553
but when you do them together it
becomes a super-duper value add

00:15:49.553 --> 00:15:52.430
because not only do you have
the peer-to-peer instruction,

00:15:52.430 --> 00:15:58.221
you use the exercises to
figure out exactly what type of
peer-to-peer instruction you needed,

00:15:58.221 --> 00:16:03.085
you know who to pair someone with because
you know maybe Sal is having trouble

00:16:03.085 --> 00:16:07.603
with level 1 exponents, Bill, we already
know has mastered level 1 exponents.

00:16:07.603 --> 00:16:11.652
So, let's set up that interaction and
then you have data on before and after.

00:16:11.652 --> 00:16:14.518
(writing) Before and after.

00:16:14.518 --> 00:16:19.806
You will even be able to assess
how good was that interaction.

00:16:19.806 --> 00:16:24.744
You can have a qualitative rating
from both the tutor and the tutee,

00:16:24.744 --> 00:16:26.621
I guess you could say or from the student.

00:16:26.621 --> 00:16:31.261
You can also have data on what happened
before and after that interaction

00:16:31.261 --> 00:16:35.320
and is it statistically significant
compared to other similar interactions.

00:16:35.320 --> 00:16:41.504
When you couple this, I really
think you are approaching
the holy grain of education.

00:16:41.504 --> 00:16:47.518
This right here is the virtual school
that I see Khan Academy growing into.

00:16:47.518 --> 00:16:51.993
Obviously these first two pieces, this
piece has been built to a large degree.

00:16:51.993 --> 00:16:56.325
I intend to continue to build it and
continue to add, really all topics.

00:16:56.325 --> 00:17:01.050
This is already starting to be
built, but I envision, right
now it goes through Algebra II,

00:17:01.050 --> 00:17:02.822
if you look at the knowledge map.

00:17:02.822 --> 00:17:08.201
I completely see more and more
of these, you can see physics
problems budding off of this,

00:17:08.201 --> 00:17:12.173
you can see calculus budding off
of this, you can see chemistry
budding off at certain points.

00:17:12.173 --> 00:17:15.969
You can see genetics problems budding off
of this, probability, you can imagine.

00:17:15.969 --> 00:17:21.814
Right now there are 70 modules,
I imagine a world where you
can have 500 or 5,000 modules.

00:17:21.814 --> 00:17:26.886
That piece can obviously built
up, you could have other types of
exercises that are complimentary,

00:17:26.886 --> 00:17:29.143
maybe emersive type exercises.

00:17:29.143 --> 00:17:31.993
Then the part that I think has a lot
of value that has yet to be built

00:17:31.993 --> 00:17:38.135
is really the peer-to-peer piece,
but all of the technology already
exists today, I think, to do it.

00:17:38.135 --> 00:17:42.546
Just to give, I think, a hint of
where I think the social value is here

00:17:42.546 --> 00:17:45.732
and I'm going to do a quick
back of the envelope calculation

00:17:45.732 --> 00:17:51.931
because I think there is a huge
amount of ... it seems appealing
to a large percentage of people

00:17:51.931 --> 00:17:58.045
but just to get an idea of how
scalable, how much leverage this
type of a concept could have,

00:17:58.045 --> 00:17:59.631
or how much social value it can create.

00:17:59.631 --> 00:18:02.953
Let's just talk about the videos alone,
let's not even talk about the exercises

00:18:02.953 --> 00:18:07.582
or the peer-to-peer interactions and let's
just talk about the videos only in English

00:18:07.582 --> 00:18:10.442
although they are already
being translated into Spanish

00:18:10.442 --> 00:18:13.286
and Tamil, and there's a group in Poland.

00:18:13.286 --> 00:18:16.112
They could very easily be translated
to every major language in the world.

00:18:16.112 --> 00:18:20.906
Let's just talk about English,
let's say we have about 500 million,

00:18:20.906 --> 00:18:25.645
(writing) There's about 500 million
English speakers world wide.

00:18:25.645 --> 00:18:29.186
That includes, I think there's
about 350 million native speakers

00:18:29.186 --> 00:18:33.846
and 150 million people who are
speaking English as a second language.

00:18:33.846 --> 00:18:36.684
Let's just say, this is a back
of the envelope calculation.

00:18:36.684 --> 00:18:42.278
Let's just say that 10% could
potentially use these type of videos,

00:18:42.278 --> 00:18:44.581
that they are at some point in
their life where they want to learn.

00:18:44.581 --> 00:18:47.401
Maybe they're teachers who want
a new way to teach something

00:18:47.401 --> 00:18:49.985
or there are people going back to college,

00:18:49.985 --> 00:18:55.986
or they are your traditional
K-12 or college student,

00:18:55.986 --> 00:18:59.583
so 10% of the population
could stand to benefit.

00:18:59.583 --> 00:19:02.239
This is, you could kind of
view this as the market,

00:19:02.239 --> 00:19:06.595
but I speak of this in kind of a social
enterprise point of view, as the market,

00:19:06.595 --> 00:19:08.769
people who could benefit from it.

00:19:08.769 --> 00:19:12.982
We're already talking about 50 million, I
actually think this number is much larger

00:19:12.982 --> 00:19:17.278
because you should include parents
and teachers and really anyone
who wants to learn anything.

00:19:17.278 --> 00:19:22.054
Let's just say 10% of the population, so
you have a 50 million addressable market,

00:19:22.054 --> 00:19:26.984
and let's say that for whatever
reason only 10% adopt the videos,

00:19:26.984 --> 00:19:30.900
I'm only talking about the videos
here, so let's just cut that down.

00:19:30.900 --> 00:19:36.319
We're talking about 10% of
the 10% addressable market of
the English speaking world,

00:19:36.319 --> 00:19:42.515
which is really only 10% of
the world, I think making very
conservative assumptions here.

00:19:42.515 --> 00:19:50.873
Sp, 10% penetration into the market
that, for whatever reason, it's
free and it's easily available

00:19:50.873 --> 00:19:55.205
and probably the most
extensive resource available,

00:19:55.205 --> 00:19:58.048
let's say just for
assumption only 10% adopt it,

00:19:58.048 --> 00:20:03.723
we're talking about 5 million
learners on a regular basis using it.

00:20:03.723 --> 00:20:07.077
Let's say that they each
watch a video roughly a week.

00:20:07.077 --> 00:20:15.756
We're talking about times say
50 video a year per person,

00:20:15.756 --> 00:20:17.851
they're just watching one video a week.

00:20:17.851 --> 00:20:21.716
The data I'm seeing right
now is people are on average
watching a video every 3 days.

00:20:21.716 --> 00:20:25.248
Actually, some of them are
watching 2, 3 videos a day,

00:20:25.248 --> 00:20:26.950
but if we average all of
the unique viewers out,

00:20:26.950 --> 00:20:30.268
it looks like they're watching a video
once every 2 or 3 days, so once a week,

00:20:30.268 --> 00:20:32.550
I think, is a very
conservative assumption.

00:20:32.550 --> 00:20:34.524
Remember, we're only talking
about the videos right now,

00:20:34.524 --> 00:20:37.528
we're not talking about even the
exercises or the peer-to-peer
instruction or all of that.

00:20:37.528 --> 00:20:43.423
If you multiply that out, you
have 250 million video views.

00:20:43.423 --> 00:20:47.120
(writing) views per year.

00:20:47.120 --> 00:20:52.190
Khan Academy isn't there right
now because it doesn't have quite
that, really that mind share yet.

00:20:52.190 --> 00:20:54.954
I don't think most people are
even aware that it even exists,

00:20:54.954 --> 00:20:57.482
but I'm talking about the reality
where people do know it exists.

00:20:57.482 --> 00:21:01.743
You have 250 million video views a year,
we're talking about only the videos,

00:21:01.743 --> 00:21:04.261
only in English, we're making
some conservative assumptions.

00:21:04.261 --> 00:21:08.567
Let's say that a video view, the
social value of a video view.

00:21:08.567 --> 00:21:15.937
(writing) Let's say the social
value, so the social value.

00:21:15.937 --> 00:21:17.889
Let's say, I don't know, it's $1.

00:21:17.889 --> 00:21:19.531
I'm just making an assumption here.

00:21:19.531 --> 00:21:21.941
My personal opinion, I think
it's far more than that.

00:21:21.941 --> 00:21:26.466
Private tutoring in any of these topics
can cost anywhere from $10 to $50

00:21:26.466 --> 00:21:29.224
and this, I think, is frankly
better than private tutoring.

00:21:29.224 --> 00:21:32.690
My cousin's have even told me that
I'm better on YouTube than I am live

00:21:32.690 --> 00:21:36.394
because it's a less stressful environment,
they can pause, they can repeat,

00:21:36.394 --> 00:21:40.826
but let's say that the social value is
$1 which I think is very conservative.

00:21:40.826 --> 00:21:47.094
Then the total social return,
that just the videos, just the
videos using these assumptions

00:21:47.094 --> 00:21:49.122
would produce, just in English ...

00:21:49.122 --> 00:21:56.252
(writing) The social return in
this scenario would be $1 times
250 million video views a year,

00:21:56.252 --> 00:22:03.183
which would be $250 million,
$250 million annually, annually.

00:22:03.183 --> 00:22:07.118
I'm not doing some type of
present value where I'm looking
at all of the future value

00:22:07.118 --> 00:22:12.685
created over the next 25 or 50
years, this is on an annual basis.

00:22:12.685 --> 00:22:14.854
This is using these
conservative estimates.

00:22:14.854 --> 00:22:19.001
If you had translated to
the top 10 languages you can
multiply this number by 10.

00:22:19.001 --> 00:22:24.573
If you make this 10% into
20% you can multiple this by
2, it will be 500 million.

00:22:24.573 --> 00:22:28.799
If you present value even this
number you're going to get
something in the billions,

00:22:28.799 --> 00:22:31.912
depending on how you present value and
your discount rate and all of that.

00:22:31.912 --> 00:22:36.620
You're going to get a number that's in
excess of multiple billions of dollars.

00:22:36.620 --> 00:22:43.320
This is all, in my mind, for a
very, very, very small relative
investment to support all of this.

00:22:43.320 --> 00:22:46.123
Remember, the social return is
calculated just from the video views.

00:22:46.123 --> 00:22:48.989
If you actually think about
it replacing actual education,

00:22:48.989 --> 00:22:53.130
you compare it to what's actually spent on
a per pupil basis in the developed world,

00:22:53.130 --> 00:22:57.395
a $10,000 per pupil then the
numbers become really ridiculous,

00:22:57.395 --> 00:23:02.294
but if you just look at the
$250 million all of this, that's
the return just on the videos,

00:23:02.294 --> 00:23:07.660
but all of this could be built,
I think, by a team of 5-10
highly motivated engineers.

00:23:07.660 --> 00:23:16.772
(writing) 5-10, built and
maintained, motivated, 5-10
engineers including myself.

00:23:16.772 --> 00:23:20.858
So, you're really talking about
an operating budget depending
on the scale you do it at

00:23:20.858 --> 00:23:24.192
on the order of a million dollars a year.

00:23:24.192 --> 00:23:29.234
The videos, obviously I can keep
going and I would pay myself
far less than a million dollars,

00:23:29.234 --> 00:23:32.195
so just there you're
getting a huge social value,

00:23:32.195 --> 00:23:36.134
but even here if you're
looking at an operating budget
of a million dollars a year

00:23:36.134 --> 00:23:43.965
you really are talking about something
that has the impact to transform
education on a world wide basis

00:23:43.965 --> 00:23:49.208
and have a social return well,
well in excess of what I think
of this as kind of the base case.

00:23:49.208 --> 00:23:50.708
Even if this was the best case,

00:23:50.708 --> 00:23:57.441
a million dollar a year
getting a $250 million a year
payback is pretty tremendous.

00:23:57.441 --> 00:23:59.937
The last thing I want to highlight
is that this is all evergreen,

00:23:59.937 --> 00:24:05.167
this is all evergreen, these
videos and these modules they don't
have to be changed every year.

00:24:05.167 --> 00:24:08.267
Math and Science does
not change that fast.

00:24:08.267 --> 00:24:11.983
Once some of this, once most
of this content is built out,

00:24:11.983 --> 00:24:17.191
if I, God forbid, got hit by
a bus tomorrow, this social
return will still exist.

00:24:17.191 --> 00:24:20.733
It's not like as soon as these engineers
disappear that all of this disappears.

00:24:20.733 --> 00:24:23.378
As long as this is maintained
by some skeleton crew,

00:24:23.378 --> 00:24:28.929
you will still continue to generate
this much in social return.

00:24:28.929 --> 00:24:31.444
Anyway, I want to leave you there
and hopefully that gives you a sense

00:24:31.444 --> 00:24:35.637
of what I see Khan Academy, what
it is today, what I see it becoming

00:24:35.637 --> 00:24:39.637
and, I think, a sense of the real
value that this can have for the world.

